Summer arrivals included [[Thomas Mavros]], [[Nikos Christidis]], [[Petros Ravousis]] and [[Takis Nikoloudis]].

The clubs most memorable moment in European competitions was the campaign to the semi-final of the [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] during the [[1976â77 UEFA Cup|1976â77]] season under [[FrantiÅ¡ek Fadrhonc]]'s management. In the way to the semi-final AEK Athens managed to eliminate four clubs. In the [[1976â77 UEFA Cup#First round|first round]] they faced [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] champions [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]]. In [[Athens]] won 2â0 with [[Goal (sport)|goals]] by [[Takis Nikoloudis]] and [[Mimis Papaioannou]]. In [[Moscow]], Dynamo paid them back by winning 2â0 and leading the match to [[extra time]]. In the last minute of extra time, AEK Athens managed to score thanks to a [[penalty kick]] by [[Tasos Konstantinou]] and proceeded to the [[1976â77 UEFA Cup#Second round|second round]]. They were drawn against [[England|English]] 4th placed side [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]]. In Athens a goal by [[Walter Wagner (footballer)|Walter Wagner]] and an [[own goal]] by [[Rod Thomas]] gave AEK the 2-0 win. In [[Derby]] AEK Athens found themselves behind in the score line but responded scoring three times with Takis Nikoloudis, Tasos Konstantinou and Walter Wagner. Derby Country only managed to score a consolation goal and the match ended in a 2-3 win for AEK Athens. In the [[1976â77 UEFA Cup#Third round|third round]] AEK Athens had to oppose [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] giants [[Red Star Belgrade]]. In Athens AEK was once again victorious by winning 2-0. [[Mimis Papaioannou]] and [[Thomas Mavros]] were the goal-scorers. In [[Belgrade]] Red Star took the lead with a goal by [[Petar BaraliÄ]] but Walter Wagner quickly equalised. The two additional goals scored by [[Zoran FilipoviÄ]] and [[DuÅ¡an SaviÄ]] were not enough and AEK Athens won on [[Away goals rule|away goals]]. In the [[1976â77 UEFA Cup#Quarter-finals|quarter-final]] AEK Athens faced their greatest challenge to that moment, English league's runner-up side [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|QPR]]. The first leg was played in [[London]]. The two penalty kick goals in the first ten minutes scored by [[Gerry Francis]] and another one scored by [[Stan Bowles]] gave QPR the 3â0 win and what looked like a certain qualification. Nevertheless AEK Athens made the impossible possible. With two goals by Thomas Mavros and ano more by Mimis Papaioannou AEK Athens sent the match to extra time and eventually to a [[Penalty shootout (association football)|penalty shootout]]. Three minutes before the final whistle, [[FrantiÅ¡ek Fadrhonc]] had [[Nikos Christidis]] substitute [[Lakis Stergioudas]], the team's regular [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]]. His move proved vital as Nikos Christidis saved two penalties and gave AEK Athens a 7-6 win. In the [[1976â77 UEFA Cup#Semi-finals|semi-finals]] draw AEK Athens were to play either Italian league's runner-up side [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] or Spanish league's third placed side [[Athletic Bilbao]]. Ultimately AEK Athens had to face the Italians. In [[Turin]], Juventus scored first with [[Antonello Cuccureddu]] but AEK Athens responded with a goal by [[Lefteris Papadopoulos]]. Two goals by [[Roberto Bettega]] and one by [[Franco Causio]] followed, giving Juventus a 4-1 victory. Juventus also won in [[Nikos Goumas Stadium]] thanks to a goal scored by [[Roberto Boninsegna]] end went on to win their first European title.

===Overview===

Under Fadrhonc's management the club performed well and although they did not manage to win any title they set the basis for the successes which followed.

