AEK Athens chairman Makis Psomiadis replaced popular head coach [[Fernando Santos (Portuguese footballer)|Fernando Santos]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=23378.html |title=Santos quits AEK |date=2002-05-09 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> with former AEK Athens legend [[DuÅ¡an BajeviÄ]]. This decision was not received well by hardcore fans [[Original 21]] who protested because they considered his move to rivals [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] six year ago as high treason. Despite the open hostility towards Bajevic the signings of [[Vassilis Borbokis]] and [[Grigoris Georgatos]] spread optimism for a successful season.

AEK Athens' unbeaten run in the [[2002â03 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] was the highlight of the season. The club played against Cypriot champions [[APOEL F.C.|APOEL]] in the [[2002â03 UEFA Champions League#Third qualifying round|third qualifying round]]. In the first leg in [[Nicosia]] APOEL scored first with [[Marinos Ouzounidis]] but AEK Athens managed to take the lead with [[Vassilis Borbokis|Vasilis Borbokis]] scoring twice. A late equaliser by [[Costas Malekkos]] did not prove enough for APOEL as [[Demis Nikolaidis]] scored during stoppage time giving his club the win. In [[Athens]] AEK Athens won thanks to a header by [[Mauricio Wright]] and entered the [[2002â03 UEFA Champions League#Group stage|group stage]] where they were drawn against [[Belgian Pro League|Belgian]] champions [[K.R.C. Genk|Racing Genk]], [[Serie A|Italian]] runner-up side [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] and UEFA Champions League's holders [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]]. AEK Athens secured two goalless draws agains Racing Genk in [[Genk]] and Roma in Athens before confronting Real Madrid. Defending champions Madrid drew 3-3 with AEK, but were twice behind against the Greek side. [[Vassilios Tsiartas|Vasilis Tsiartas]] became the first player to score against the Spanish side in this season's competition with a sixth-minute [[Direct free kick|free-kick]]. However, Madrid were soon back on level terms thanks to [[Zinedine Zidane]]'s goal after 15 minutes before further goals from [[Christos Maladenis]] and Demis Nikolaidis put the hosts in the driving seat. However, another Zidane strike and a second-half [[Guti (footballer)|Guti]] goal ensured Madrid left with a point<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=36428.html |title=AEK give Madrid a fright |date=2002-10-03 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>. An in a way opposite match was played in [[Madrid]] where [[Steve McManaman]]'s two goals put Real Madrid in front during half-time and AEK Athens equilised with goal by [[Kostas Katsouranis]] and [[Walter Centeno]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=39412.html |title=Substitutions fire AEK revival |date=2002-10-23 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>. The next match was agains Racing Genk in Athens. Racing Genk scored first and AEK Athens responded with [[Vassilis Lakis|Vasilis Lakis]] scoring. The group stage was concluded in [[Rome]] agains Roma where AEK Athens was once again behind in the scoreline by a goal scored by [[Marco Delvecchio]] but managed to score a late equiliser with Walter Centeno. The six draws AEK Athens secured are a feat no other club has ever accomplished.

The team continued in the [[2002â03 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] and smashed Israeli champions [[Maccabi Haifa F.C.|Maccabi Haifa]] by achieving two of their biggest wins ever in European competitions. They first won in Athens 4-0 with goals by [[Grigoris Georgatos]], Demis Nikolaidis, [[Milen Petkov]] and [[Theodoros Zagorakis|Thodoris Zagorakis]] and then 4-1 in Nicosia with two goals by Vasilis Lakis and two more by Kostas Katsouranis and [[Dimitris Nalitzis]]. [[Walid Badir]] had earlier scored a penalty kick for Maccabi Haifa. AEK Athens' run was brought to an end in the [[2002â03 UEFA Cup#Fourth round|last-16 round]] by Spanish side [[MÃ¡laga CF|MÃ¡laga]]. They drew 0-0 in [[MÃ¡laga]] but lost 0-1 in Athens thanks to a goal by [[Antonio Manuel SÃ¡nchez GÃ³mez|Manu]].

The season was also punctuated by the demolition of [[Nikos Goumas Stadium]], home to AEK for over 70 years, and the assault of club president Makis Psomiadis and his bodyguards to the team captain [[Demis Nikolaidis]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=gre/news/newsid=50062.html |title=Nikolaidis in dispute with AEK |date=2003-01-13 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>.

===2003â04 season===

[[File:Ioannis Okkas.jpg|thumb |right |200px |[[Ioannis Okkas|Giannis Okkas]] playing for [[Cyprus national football team|Cyprus]].]]

{{main|2003â04 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

After seven years wearing AEK Athens' number 11 shirt during which he scored 125 goals in the [[Superleague Greece|Alpha Ethniki]], and partly due to the clubâs growing financial problems from mismanagement<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=gre/news/newsid=72426.html |title=Psomiadis charged over missing millions |date=2003-05-30 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>, [[Demis Nikolaidis]] terminated his contract by mutual consent and signed for [[AtlÃ©tico Madrid]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=81083.html |title=Nikolaidis seals Spanish switch |date=2003-07-13 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>. The transfers of [[Nikos Liberopoulos]] from [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=87400.html |title=Liberopoulos lands at AEK |date=2003-08-01 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> and [[Ioannis Okkas|Giannis Okkas]] from [[P.A.O.K. F.C.|P.A.O.K.]] promised to revitalise the clubâs on-field success amid the growing financial problems. Modest performances, though, were not enough as more off-field dramas unfolded. Unable to cope with the negativity from a large section of AEK Athens fans, BajeviÄ resigned in 2004 during a season match against [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.|Iraklis]] and [[Ilie Dumitrescu]] was appointed as a caretaker manager.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=142174.html |title=Dumitrescu takes over at AEK |date=2004-02-02 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>

===Overview===
Under BajeviÄ's management the club generally perform well, especially in his first season. They played a total of 82 matches winning 45 of them and drawing in 23 more. They scored a total of 166 goals conceding 78.

==The Fernando Santos Era, Part II (2004â2006)==

''Honours Won: â''

''Runner-up: Alpha Ethniki ([[2005â06 Alpha Ethniki|2006]]), Greek Cup ([[2005â06 Greek Cup|2006]])''

===2004â05 season===

[[File:Bruno Alves.jpg|thumb |left |200px |[[Bruno Alves]], here playing for [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit]], joined AEK Athens on loan from [[F.C. Porto|Porto]].]]

[[File:Notias.jpg|thumb |right |200px |[[Nicholas X. Notias|Nikos Notias]], one of AEK Athens new shareholders (2009-06-02).]]

{{main|2004â05 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

On the brink of bankruptcy, and losing most of its [[UEFA Euro 2004]] stars and experienced players to other European clubs, AEK needed a miracle to prevent it from being relegated to the Greek amateur leagues. Though both [[Kostas Katsouranis]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=209806.html |title=Katsouranis stays at AEK |date=2004-07-25 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> and [[Nikos Liberopoulos]] remained, [[Vassilis Borbokis]], [[Grigoris Georgatos]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=131253.html |title=Georgatos quits AEK |date=2003-12-04 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> [[UEFA Euro 2004]] MVP [[Theodoros Zagorakis|Theodoris Zagorakis]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=207407.html |title=Zagorakis release alerts Europe |date=2004-07-14 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> [[Michalis Kapsis]], [[Michalis Kasapis]], [[Michel Kreek]], [[Vassilis Lakis]], [[Vassilios Tsiartas|Vassilis Tsiartas]], and [[Ioannis Okkas|Giannis Okkas]] all left the club in the wake of the troubles.

In was then when [[Demis Nikolaidis]] persuaded a group of businessmen (including [[Nicholas X. Notias|Nikos Notias]], [[Petros Pappas]], [[Takis Kannelopoulos]], [[Gikas Goumas]] and [[Polis Hatziioannou]]) to buy shares and invest money to the club and became the new club president with the help of all AEK fans who started mass protests organized by the hardcore fans [[Original 21]]. His primary task was to lead AEK Athens out of its precarious financial position. The first success was an arrangement through the Greek justice system to write off most of the massive debt that previous club administrators had amassed, and to repay any remaining public debts in manageable instalments. Securing the clubâs existence in the Alpha Ethniki, Nikolaidis then began a program to rebuild AEK to its former glory. He appointed experienced former player [[Ilija IviÄ]] as technical director of the club and brought back [[Fernando Santos (Portuguese footballer)|Fernando Santos]] as head coach.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=208245.html |title=Santos returns to AEK |date=2004-07-16 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> The AEK Athens fans, emboldened by Nikolaidisâs efforts, followed suit by buying season ticket packages in record numbers (over 17,000). AEK Athens recruited mostly young Greek players led by Katsouranis and Liberopoulos to form a competitive team.

With the winter additions of [[JÃºlio CÃ©sar da Silva e Souza|JÃºlio CÃ©sar]] and [[Serbia national football team|Serbian]] international [[Vladimir IviÄ]] AEK Athens came close to winning the [[Alpha Ethniki 2004â05|2004â05 Alpha Ethniki]] but a surprise loss to underdogs [[Ionikos F.C.|Ionikos]] cost them the title. Furthermore a serius mistake by [[referee]] [[Kyros Vassaras]] made them lose the chance to compte in the [[UEFA Champions League]] [[2005â06 UEFA Champions League qualifying rounds#Third qualifying round|third qualifying round]].

