{{main|2006â07 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

President [[Demis Nikolaidis]] appointed former [[Real Betis]] manager [[Lorenzo Serra Ferrer]] as head coach<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=428148.html |title=Serra Ferrer takes AEK reins |date=2006-06-07 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> so that AEK Athens could play a more attacking style of football.

[[Kostas Katsouranis]] was transferred to [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] for â¬2.5M.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=431794.html |title=Katsouranis joins Santos at Benfica |date=2006-06-22 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> Summer transfers included [[Greece national football team|Greek]] internationals [[Panagiotis Lagos]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=436340.html |title=Lagos acquired by AEK |date=2006-07-12 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> and [[Akis Zikos]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=444873.html |title=Zikos returns to AEK |date=2006-08-14 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> and the loan of [[Gustavo Manduca]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=441977.html |title=AEK make Manduca move |date=2006-08-04 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>

His season started well as AEK Athens easily overcame [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Hearts]] in the [[2006â07 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] [[2006â07 UEFA Champions League qualifying rounds#Third qualifying round|third qualifying round]] by beating them twice, thus qualifing to the [[2006â07 UEFA Champions League group stage|group stage]]. In the group stage the club obtained 8 points, their top performance until then, beating [[Lille OSC|Lille]], 1â0 goal by [[Nikos Liberopoulos]], and [[A.C. Milan|Milan]], 1â0 goal by [[JÃºlio CÃ©sar da Silva e Souza|JÃºlio CÃ©sar]], in their way to the third place.

In the [[2006â07 Superleague Greece|Superleague]] AEK Athens finished second securing a place in the [[2007â08 UEFA Champions League]] [[2007â08 UEFA Champions League qualifying rounds#Third qualifying round|third qualifying round]].

During the winter transfer period AEK Athens signed [[Greece national football team|Greek]] international [[Pantelis Kafes]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=501835.html |title=AEK pick up unattached Kafes |date=2007-01-29 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>

===2007â08 season, Part I===

[[File:Original21AEK.jpg|thumb |left |200px |[[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]] fans during the match against [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]] (2007-09-03).]]

{{main|2007â08 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

The season started with great expectations for AEK Athens as they signed [[Argentinian people|Argentine]] international [[Rodolfo Arruabarrena]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=534257.html |title=Arruabarrena acquired by AEK |date=2007-05-02 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> [[Brazilian people|Brazilian]] football legend [[Rivaldo]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=544579.html |title=AEK ambition appeals to Rivaldo |date=2007-05-30 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> and [[Ismael Blanco]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=569930.html |title=AEK seal Blanco deal |date=2007-08-12 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> [[Gustavo Manduca|Gustavo Manduca's]] loan move was made permanent.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=539439.html |title=AEK make Manduca move permanent |date=2007-05-17 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>

After two years together AEK Athens and [[Adidas]] went on separate ways and the kit sponsor switched to [[Puma AG|Puma]].

For the 2007â08 UEFA Champions League third qualifying round AEK Athens were drawn with [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] and [[Copa del Rey]] holders, [[Sevilla FC|Sevilla]], and were easily eliminated losing both games. The second match was postponed<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=576048.html |title=AEK-Sevilla match postponed |date=2007-08-29 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> due to the death of [[Antonio Puerta]] due to [[cardiac arrest]] and a [[moment of silence]] was held prior to the game. After being eliminated from the [[UEFA Champions League]] AEK Athens were drawn to play [[Austrian Football Bundesliga|Austrian]] champions [[FC Red Bull Salzburg|Red Bull Salzburg]] in the [[UEFA Cup]]. On September 20 in [[Athens]], AEK Athens defeated Red Bull Salzburg 3-0. The second leg was played in [[Salzburg]] on October 4 AEK Athens lost the match but still went through 3-1 on agg. On October 9 AEK Athens were drawn in Group C in the UEFA Cup group stage along with [[La Liga|Spanish]] fifth placed side [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]], [[Serie A|Italian]] sixth placed side [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]], [[Gambrinus liga|Czech]] third placed side [[FK MladÃ¡ Boleslav|MladÃ¡ Boleslav]], and [[Allsvenskan|Swedish]] champions [[IF Elfsborg|Elfsborg]].On October 25 AEK Athens kicked off the group stage's with a 1-1 draw away to Elfsborg, on November 29 AEK Athens again drew 1-1, this time at home to Fiorentina. On December 5 AEK Athens won Mlada Boleslav 1-0 away and on December 20 although AEK Athens was home defeated 1-2 by Villarreal, finally booked a place in the knockout stage of the [[UEFA Cup]], finishing third in the group.

The [[2007â08 Superleague Greece|Greek Superleague's]] opening season games were postponed by the [[Hellenic Football Federation|EPO]] due to the [[2007 Greek forest fires]] in the [[Peloponnese]]. Nevertheless AEK Athens started with six straight wins withou conceding a single goal until an unexpected home loss in the hands of [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.|Iraklis]].

===Overview===
Under Ferrer's management the club generally perform well. They played a total of 71 matches winning 39 of them and drawing in 13 more. They scored a total of 122 goals conceding 67.

