[[Image:Dellas 2008.jpg|thumb |left |150px |[[Traianos Dellas]], with [[Greece national football team|Greece]] (2008-06-01).]]

{{main|2007â08 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

On 12 February 2008 AEK parted company with [[Lorenzo Serra Ferrer]] after a poor run of form and un-successful signings and replaced him with former player and then assistant manager [[Nikos Kostenoglou]], on a caretaker basis, at the end of an indifferent season. The team had an impressive run in the last ten games of the league, during which they had two 4-0 wins against [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] and [[PAOK F.C.|PAOK]], finishing in first place. Nevertheless the team ultimately finished second due to a court case between [[Apollon Kalamarias F.C.|Apollon Kalamaria]] and Olympiacos for the illegal usage of [[Roman Wallner]] in Apollon Kalamaria's 1-0 win earlier in the season. Olympiacos were awarded the three points in a court hearing, thus finishing two points ahead of AEK. AEK president [[Demis Nikolaidis]] and several other managers and chairmen have been angered with the court's decision stating that the [[Hellenic Football Federation]] knew about the usage of the illegal player prior to the game but didn't do anything about it.

The second place meant that the club had to compete in the league's play-offs but AEK Athens' captains, MVP performer [[Rivaldo]] and president [[Demis Nikolaidis]] did not want to compete as they considered themselves champions. [[Akis Zikos]] preferred to retire after the league's last game against [[Asteras Tripoli F.C.|Asteras Tripoli]] than compete in the play-offs. Nevertheless, the clubs stakeholders insisted that the club had to compete and the ultimately did. The clubs low morale resulted in disastrous results, including a 4-1 loss against [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] and a 4-0 loss against [[Aris Thessaloniki F.C.|Aris]]. They finishing second in the play-offs missing the opportunity to compete in the [[UEFA Champions League]] during the nest season.

===Overview===
Under Kostenoglou's management the club had mixed performances, excellend in the domestic league yet disappointing in the UEFA Cup and the play-offs. They played a total of 18 matches winning 10 of them and drawing in 5 more. They scored a total of 35 goals conceding 19.

==The Giorgos Donis Era (2008)==

''Honours Won: â''

''Runner-up: â''

===2008â09 season, Part I===

[[Image:Scocco.jpg|thumb |left |150px |[[Ignacio Scocco|Nacho Scocco]], here in training with [[Club Universidad Nacional|Pumas]].]]

[[Image:AEK Shirt 2008-2009.jpg|thumb |right |150px |2008-09 Home kit]]

[[Image:AEK Shirt 2nd and 3rd 2008-2009.jpg|thumb |right |150px |2008-09 Away and 3rd kit]]

{{main|2008â09 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

[[Giorgos Donis]], former head coach of [[2006â07 Greek Cup]] winners [[AEL 1964 FC|Larissa]], was appointed as head coach of AEK Athens.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=gre/news/newsid=696219.html |title=Donis handed AEK post |date=2008-05-14 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> There were big changes in the squad with the club spending almost [[Euro sign|â¬]]8M in signings including [[Sweden|Swedish]] international [[Daniel MajstoroviÄ]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=swe/news/newsid=698035.html |title=AEK move for Basel's Majstorovic |date=2008-05-19 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> [[Ignacio Scocco|Nacho Scocco]], [[Argentina national football team|Argentine]] international [[SebastiÃ¡n Saja]], [[Spain|Spanish]] international [[Juan Francisco GarcÃ­a|Juanfran]], [[Greece national football team|Greece's]] captain [[Angelos Basinas]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=736179.html |title=Basinas back home with AEK |date=2008-07-31 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> [[Greece|Greek]] international [[Sotirios Kyrgiakos|Sotiris Kyrgiakos]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=736442.html |title=AEK add Kyrgiakos to ranks |date=2008-08-02 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> and [[Algeria]]n international [[Rafik Djebbour]] and the simultaneous departure of all tree [[Captain (association football)|captains]] and club legends [[Akis Zikos]], [[Traianos Dellas]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=734478.html |title=Dellas and AEK part company |date=2008-07-23 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> and [[Nikos Liberopoulos]] combined with young starlet [[Sokratis Papastathopoulos|Sokratis Papastathopoulos']] transfer to [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]]. On top of that [[Brazilian people|Brazilian]] legend [[Rivaldo]] who was the new captain asked, and was ultimately given, a last minute thansfer to [[Uzbeks|Uzbeki]] side [[FC Bunyodkor|Bunyodkor]].

The season started in the worst way possible as AEK Athens failed to surpass [[AC Omonia|Omonia]] (0-1 in [[Athens]], 2-2 in [[Nicosia]]) for [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup's]] [[2008â09 UEFA Cup#Second qualifying round|second qualifying round]] second qualifying round resulting their elimination from European competitions, the earliest on in ther history.

The league campaign started very well due to the 2-1 [[Local derby|derby]] win over [[AEK and Panathinaikos rivalry|rivals]] [[Panathinaikos F.C.|Panathinaikos]] thanks to goals by [[Arnaldo Edi Lopes da Silva|Edinho]] and [[Ismael Blanco]] in the opening game but a series of poor performances and results left AEK Athens in a difficult situation. Donis was eager to leave the club after drawing 3-3 against underdogs [[Thrasyvoulos F.C.|Thrasyvoulos]] despite having a 0-3 [[half-time]] lead, but president [[Demis Nikolaidis]] did not allow him to leave. Nevertheless, Nikolaidis left shortly after due to the continuous disappointing results, the heavy criticism he took from the fans and the press for the disbandment of last year's championship winning team and a lengthy clash with the club's hardcore supporters [[Original 21]]. The presidency was temporarily taken by Nikos Koulis and Takis Kanellopoulos. However, the series of disappointing results continued, bringing anger and insecure situations for everyone in the team. The first to be hit by this wave of disappointment and with the council of the team upset, was Donis, who was asked to leave the team after a 0-0 home draw against [[Panserraikos F.C.|Panserraikos]].

===Overview===
Under Donis' management the club did not perform well. They played a total of 13 matches winning 4 of them and drawing in 7 more. They scored a total of 17 goals while conceding 16.

==The DuÅ¡an BajeviÄ Era, Part III (2008â2010)==

''Honours Won: â''

''Runner-up: [[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: 1 ([[2008â09 Greek Cup|2009]])''

===2008â09 season, Part II===

[[File:Oli vs larrisa 5.jpg|thumb |left |150px |[[Olivier N'Siabamfumu]], the sole winter addition to the squad.]]

[[File:Ismael Blanco 2009.jpg|thumb |right |150px |[[Ismael Blanco]], top scorer in the [[2008â09 Superleague Greece|Greek Superleague]] and the [[2008â09 Greek Cup|Greek Cup]]]]

{{main|2008â09 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

On November 21, 2008, Koulis and Kanellopoulos hired [[DuÅ¡an BajeviÄ]] as head coach for the third time. However after a while and because of the controversy surrounding BajeviÄ's return to AEK Athens a rivalry sparked between him and Kanellopoulos resulting in the latterâs resign from the presidency.

[[Georgios Kintis]] became the team's new president shortly after but did not last long as on February 4, 2009 Nikos Thanopoulos was elected as number 41 president of AEK Athens.

During the winter transfer period [[Edson Ramos Silva|Edson Ratinho]] and [[Greece national football team|Greece's]] captain [[Angelos Basinas]] left the club. The only addition to the squad was [[Olivier N'Siabamfumu]].

Bajevic brought some much-needed stability to the club, and performances on the pitch improved vastly towards the end of the season, culminating in AEK's progression to the [[2008â09 Greek Cup|Greek Cup]] [[2008â09 Greek Cup#Final|final]] against [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]. Although they took an early 2-0 lead, thanks to two goals by [[Ismael Blanco]], and a 3-2 lead, thanks to a stoppage time goal by [[Ignacio Scocco|Nacho Scocco]], the march ended in a 4-4 draw and the winner would be decided in a penalty shootout in which AEK Athens lost 14-15 due to three penalties misses by [[Daniel Majstorovic]], [[Nikolaos Georgeas|Nikos Georgeas]] and [[Agustin Pelletieri]].

AEK Athens finished fourth in the [[2008â09 Superleague Greece|Greek Superleague]], thus qualifying for the seasons [[2008â09 Superleague Greece#Play-offs|play-offs]].

In the play-offs they secured the second place just missing out the [[UEFA Champions League]] [[2009â10 UEFA Champions League qualifying phase and play-off round#Third qualifying round|third qualifying round]] ticket. Instead AEK Athens would compete in the newly founded [[2009â10 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]].

[[Ismael Blanco]] finished the season with a total 23 goals, 14 of which were scored in the [[2008â09 Superleague Greece|Greek Superleague]] earning him his second consecutive title of [[List of top goalscorers in Superleague Greece by season|Greek Superleague top goalscorer]]. He was also the top goalscorer of the Greek Cup.

