[[File:Sotirios Kyrgiakos 2011.jpg|thumb |left |150px |[[Sotirios Kyrgiakos|Sotiris Kyrgiakos']] last minute move to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] was a shock to averyone in the club (2011-07-23)]]

[[File:Dynamo stadium Minsk Europa league BATE-AEK.JPG|thumb |left |150px |AEK lining up in [[Dynama Stadium (Minsk)|Dynama Stadium]], [[Minsk]] (2009-10-22).]]

{{main|2009â10 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

During the summer transfer period AEK Athens signed mainly player from the Greek league including [[Kostas Manolas]], [[Greeks|Greek]] international [[Grigoris Makos]] and [[Leonardo Rodriguez Pereira|Leonardo]]. They also signed naturalized [[Poles|Polish]] international [[Roger Guerreiro|Roger]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=878744.html |title='Destiny' takes Roger to AEK |date=2009-08-27 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>

The season started badly due to the last minute 3 million [[Euro]]s transfer of team captain [[Sotirios Kyrgiakos|Sotiris Kyrgiakos]] to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=875572.html |title=Kyrgiakos lined up by Liverpool |date=2009-08-20 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> the 2-1 loss to [[Liga I|Romanian]] fifth placed side [[FC Vaslui|Vaslui]] for the first lef of the [[UEFA Europa League]] [[2009â10 UEFA Europa League qualifying phase and play-off round#Play-off round|play-off round]] and [[DuÅ¡an BajeviÄ|DuÅ¡an BajeviÄ's]] altercation with the club's all-time highest paid transfer [[Rafik Djebbour]] which resulted to the latter not training or playing with the rest of the squad. Despite the difficulties AEK Athens won 3-0 in the second leg, thanks to goals by [[Gustavo Manduca]] and [[Ignacio Scocco|Nacho Scocco]] (x2), and qualified for the UEFA Europa League [[2009â10 UEFA Europa League group stage#Group I|group stage]].

In a group featuring [[Primeira Liga|Portuguese]] third placed side [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]], [[Premier League|English]] fifth placed side [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], and [[Belarusian Premier League|Belarusian]] champions [[FC BATE Borisov|BATE]], AEK Athens secured only a 1-0 victory against Benfica thanks to a header by [[Daniel Majstorovic]] and a gathered total of four points.

On top of that AEK Athens failed to progress from the [[2009â10 Greek Cup|Greek Cup]] [[2009â10 Greek Cup#Fourth round|fourth round]] as they lost 0-1 front to [[Football League (Greece)|Beta Ethniki]] underdogs [[Thrasyvoulos F.C.|Thrasyvoulos]].

In the [[2009â10 Superleague Greece|Superleague]] AEK Athens failed to impress with their most memorable moment being a 2-1 away victory against rivals [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] thanks to two goals scored by [[Ignacio Scocco|Nacho Scocco]]. They finished fourth and qualified for the Superleague [[2009â10 Superleague Greece|play-offs]].

In the Superleague play-offs AEK Athens secured the second place and a [[2010â11 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] [[2010â11 UEFA Europa League qualifying phase and play-off round#Play-off round|play-off round]] ticket by beating Olympiacos 2-1 thanks to goals by Kostas Manolas and [[Ismael Blanco]].

Ismael Blanco was the season's top scorer for the club bagging 13 goals while Gustavo Manduca and Nacho Scocco were the top assist men with 5 assists each.

===2010â11 season, Part I===


[[File:Papa Bouba Diop.png|thumb |right |125px |[[Papa Bouba Diop]], AEK's 2010 coup signing, here with [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].]]

{{main|2010â11 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

In the 2010 summer transfer period AEK Athens chose to sign more experienced players including [[Greeks|Greek]] internationals and former AEK Athens captains [[Nikos Liberopoulos]] and [[Traianos Dellas]], [[Greeks|Greek]] international [[Christos Patsatzoglou]] and [[Senegal national football team|Senegal's]] [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] hero [[Papa Bouba Diop]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=1505308.html |title=Bouba Diop makes AEK Athens move |date=2010-07-15 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>.

AEK Athens had a very good pre-season easily winning the inaugural [[2010 Sydney Festival of Football]].

AEK Athens qualified from the [[2010â11 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] [[2010â11 UEFA Europa League qualifying phase and play-off round#Play-off round|play-off round]] surpassing [[Scottish Premier League|Scottish]] third placed side [[Dundee United F.C.|Dundee United]]. In the [[2010â11 UEFA Europa League group stage#Group G|group stage]] they were drawn against [[Russian Premier League|Russia]] third placed side [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit]], [[Belgian Pro League|Belgian]] champions [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]] and [[Prva HNL|Croatian]] runner-up side [[HNK Hajduk Split|Hajduk Split]].

In the [[2010â11 Superleague Greece|Greek Superleague]] despite having a favourable schedule AEK Athens lost twice (against [[Kerkyra F.C.|Kerkyra]] and [[Ethnikos Olympiakos Volos F.C.|Olympiakos Volou]]) and drew once (against [[Asteras Tripoli F.C.|Asteras Tripoli]]) in their four first matches.

[[DuÅ¡an BajeviÄ]] resigned on September 26, 2010 after a 3-1 loss against Olympiakos Volou<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=1536653.html |title=BajeviÄ calls time on AEK again |date=2010-09-27 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>.

[[Bledar Kola]] was appointed as a caretaker manager.

===Overview===
Under Bajevic's management the club performed badly. They played a total of 84 matches winning 39 of them and drawing in 24 more. They scored a total of 116 goals conceding 87.

