[[File:ManoloJimenez.jpg|thumb |left |150px |[[Manuel JimÃ©nez JimÃ©nez|Manolo JimÃ©nez]], AEK's new head coach, here with Sevilla (2010-02-23).]]

{{main|2010â11 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

On 9 October 2010 [[Manuel JimÃ©nez JimÃ©nez|Manolo JimÃ©nez]] agreed a two-year deal with AEK Athens<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=1544207.html |title=JimÃ©nez replaces BajeviÄ as AEK coach |date=2010-10-08 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>.

Results were instantly improved and AEK Athens won both derby matches against [[Panathinaikos FC|Panathinaikos]] and [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]] by 1-0 and secured an impressive 0-4 away victory against [[Aris F.C. (Thessaloniki)|Aris]]. They also beat [[PAOK F.C.|PAOK]] 4-0 thanks to goals by [[Papa Bouba Diop]], [[Ignacio Scocco|Nacho Scocco]] (x2) and [[Traianos Dellas]].

AEK Athens moved to a new training complex in [[Spata]] on November, 2010. The complex was built using funds of AEK Athens shareholder [[Nicholas X. Notias|Nikos Notias]].

During the winter transfer period AEK Athens signed [[Morocco national football team|Moroccan]] international [[Nabil Baha]] and [[Croatia national football team|Croatian]] international [[Dino DrpiÄ]] and loaned [[Miguel Marcos Madera|MÃ­chel]] and [[David Mateos]].

In the [[2010â11 Greek Cup|Greek Cup]] AEK Athens easily surpassed [[AEL 1964 FC|Larissa]] with an 0-4 away victory thanks to goals by [[Ismael Blanco]], [[Nikolaos Georgeas|Nikos Georgeas]], [[Rafik Djebbour]] and [[Kostas Manolas]]. In the [[2010â11 Greek Cup#Quarter-Finals|quarter-finals]] they faced [[AEK and Panathinaikos rivalry|rivals]] Panathinaikos. Two goals by [[Nikos Liberopoulos]] secured a 0-2 away victory which seamed to be enough to secure qualification. In the second leg [[Panagiotis Lagos]] scored first for AEK Athens by the went on to concede three goals. A last stoppage time goal thanks to a long range free kick by [[Miguel Marcos Madera|MÃ­chel]] gave AEK Athens a place in the [[2010â11 Greek Cup#Semi-Finals|semi-finals]] where the whould face [[PAOK F.C.|PAOK]]. The first game was held in [[Athens]] and ended in a 0-0 draw with the woodwork coming to PAOK's rescue twice after powerful headers by [[Papa Bouba Diop]]. In [[Salonica]] AEK Athens secured a 0-1 win and a place in the final thanks to a header by their captain Traianos Dellas. The final against [[Atromitos F.C.|Atromitos]] proved easy and thanks to goals by [[Nikos Liberopoulos]], [[Nabil Baha]] and [[Pantelis Kafes]] they won 3-0 winning the Greek Cup.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=gre/news/newsid=1625535.html |title=AEK Athens claim Greek Cup honours |date=2011-04-30 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>

In the [[2010â11 Superleague Greece#Playoffs|Superleague playoffs]] AEK Athens made a good start with two home wins (against [[Ethnikos Olympiakos Volos F.C.|Olympiakos Volou]] and [[P.A.O.K. F.C.|P.A.O.K.]]) and an away draw against Panathinaikos but lost all tree remaining matches finishing third.

===2011â12 season, Part I===

[[File:Eidur Gudjohnsen 10mar2007.jpg|thumb |right |150px |[[EiÃ°ur GuÃ°johnsen]], AEK's 2011 coup signing, here playing for [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] (2007-05-10).]]

{{main|2011â12 AEK Athens F.C. season}}

The transfer of [[Ignacio Scocco|Nacho Scocco]] to [[Al Ain S.C.C.|Al Ain]] in the [[United Arab Emirates]] brought 2.8 million [[Euro]]s to AEK Athens yet combined with the deparure of [[Argentina national football team|Argentine]] international [[SebastiÃ¡n Saja]] and [[Miguel Marcos Madera|MÃ­chel]] greatly depowered the squad. Furthemore [[Papa Bouba Diop]] had to leave the team as his wife experienced [[Complications of pregnancy|complications]] during her pregnancy. To compensate for these departures AEK Athens signed former [[Iceland national football team|Iceland's]] captain [[EiÃ°ur GuÃ°johnsen]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=1651854.html |title=Gudjohnsen proud to sign for AEK Athens |date=2011-07-19 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref> [[JosÃ© Carlos FernÃ¡ndez VÃ¡zquez|JosÃ© Carlos]] and [[Greece national football team|Greek]] international [[Dimitrios Konstantopoulos|Dimi]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=1650819.html |title=AEK add to squad with double signing |date=2011-07-13 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>. Additionally [[Steve Leo Beleck|Steve Beleck]] and [[Juan Torres Ruiz|Cala]] were signed on one year-long loan deals. They also completed the last minute signing of [[Colombia national football team|Colombian]] international [[FabiÃ¡n AndrÃ©s Vargas|FabiÃ¡n Vargas]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/news/newsid=1669872.html |title=Vargas excited to sign for AEK Athens |date=2011-08-27 |work=uefa.com |accessdate=}}</ref>

In the [[2011â12 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] [[2011â12 UEFA Europa League#Play-off round|play-off round]] AEK Athens were drawn against [[Umaglesi Liga|Georgian]] runner-up side [[FC Dinamo Tbilisi|Dinamo Tbilisi]]. In [[Athens]] AEK Athens won 1-0 thanks to a header by JosÃ© Carlos. In [[Tbilisi]] Dinamo scored a first minute goal thanks to their [[Captain (association football)#Club captain|captain]] [[Aleksandre Koshkadze]] and led the match to extra time. During extra time AEK Athens managed to equilise thanks to a penalty won by GuÃ°johnsen and taken by [[Leonardo Rodriguez Pereira|Leonardo]]. In the [[2011â12 UEFA Europa League group stage#Group L|Group Stage]] AEK Athens was drawn against [[Belgian Pro League|Belgian]] thid place side [[R.S.C. Anderlecht|Anderlecht]], [[Russian Premier League|Russia]] fifth placed side [[FC Lokomotiv Moscow|Lokomotiv Moscow]] and [[Austrian Football Bundesliga|Austrian]] champions [[SK Sturm Graz|Sturm Graz]].

The [[2011â12 Superleague Greece|Greek Superleague]] premier game for AEK Athens was postponed twice. First due to the [[Koriopolis]] [[match fixing]] scandal in [[Football in Greece|Greek football]] and then due to prime minister [[George Papandreou|George Papandreou's]] speech in the [[Thessaloniki International Trade Fair]].

In 5 October, 2011 Manolo JimÃ©nez's contract was mutually terminated following heavy defeats in the hands of Anderlecht and [[P.A.O.K. F.C.|P.A.O.K.]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.aekfc.gr/index.asp?a_id=1355&n_id=7134 |title=ÎÏÏÎ· ÏÎ·Ï ÏÏÎ½ÎµÏÎ³Î±ÏÎ¯Î±Ï Î¼Îµ ÏÎ¿Î½ Îº. Manuel Jimenez (GR) |date=2011-10-05 |work=aekfc.gr |accessdate=}}</ref>.

===Overview===

Under JimÃ©nez's management the club had mixed performances. They played a total of 59 matches winning 29 of them and drawing in 10 more. They scored a total of 89 goals conceding 74.

